# Functions

Imagine a coffee machine. You press one button and a complex sequence of steps — heat water, grind beans, extract espresso — happens automatically. You do not need to understand or repeat all those steps every time you want coffee. A **function** works the same way: you write a set of instructions once, give them a name, and call that name whenever you need those instructions executed.

## Function Declaration

```javascript
function greet(name) {
    console.log(`Hello, ${name}!`);
}

greet("Rahul");  // Hello, Rahul!
greet("Priya");  // Hello, Priya!
```

The keyword `function` starts the declaration. Inside the parentheses are **parameters** — placeholder names for the values the function will receive. The body is the block inside `{}`.

## Parameters and Arguments

- **Parameter** — the name listed in the function definition (`name` above)
- **Argument** — the actual value passed when calling the function (`"Rahul"` above)

## Returning a Value

A function that only `console.log()` is fine for output, but often you want the function to **compute** a result and send it back:

```javascript
function add(a, b) {
    return a + b;       // sends the value back to the caller
}

const sum = add(10, 5);  // sum = 15
console.log(sum);
```

A function without a `return` statement automatically returns `undefined`.

## Function Expressions

In JavaScript, functions are values. You can store them in variables:

```javascript
const multiply = function(a, b) {
    return a * b;
};

console.log(multiply(4, 5));  // 20
```

## Hoisting

Function **declarations** are hoisted — JavaScript moves them to the top of their scope, so you can call them before the line where they are defined. Function **expressions** are not hoisted.

```javascript
console.log(add(2, 3));   // 5 — works even before the declaration

function add(a, b) {
    return a + b;
}
```

In the code example below, you will see a set of pure functions that calculate invoice totals and grades.

codeExample.code:
// Pure functions — take inputs, return outputs, no side effects

function calculateGST(amount, rate) {
    return amount * rate;
}

function calculateTotal(price, quantity, gstRate) {
    const subtotal = price * quantity;
    const gst      = calculateGST(subtotal, gstRate);
    return subtotal + gst;
}

function assignGrade(score) {
    if      (score >= 90) return "A";
    else if (score >= 80) return "B";
    else if (score >= 70) return "C";
    else if (score >= 60) return "D";
    else                  return "F";
}

function formatCurrency(amount) {
    return `₹${amount.toFixed(2)}`;
}

// Use the functions
const total = calculateTotal(1500, 3, 0.18);
console.log("Total (with GST):", formatCurrency(total));

const examScores = [88, 95, 72, 55, 91];
console.log("\n--- Grades ---");
examScores.forEach((score, i) => {
    console.log(`Student ${i + 1}: ${score} → ${assignGrade(score)}`);
});

